<subSubSection pageId="24" pageNumber="153" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="24.[1373,2580,1356,2455]" pageId="24" pageNumber="153">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1374,2070,2066,2099]" pageId="24" pageNumber="153">Movements, Home range and Social organization.</emphasis>
There is no specific information for this species, but Gardner’s Short-tailed Opossum is probably ground dwelling. It has been captured in live traps set on the ground and in pitfall traps.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="24" pageNumber="153" type="conservation">
<paragraph blockId="24.[1373,2580,1356,2455]" pageId="24" pageNumber="153">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1375,1730,2184,2217]" pageId="24" pageNumber="153">Status and Conservation.</emphasis>
Gardner’s Short-tailed Opossum has not been assessed on The IUCN Red List. It does occur in at least one protected area, Yanachaga-Chemillén National Park, Pasco, but because it is known only from four localities and there is no information on population size, its status may be difficult to establish. Conservation status of all opossums is being reassessed by the [IUCN New World Marsupial Specialists Group.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
